{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a88e11a0-50e6-43ad-8cdc-03bf6bfca96a","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS and require SIP adjustments on newer versions.\n\nFor most cases, the `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is your best bet — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c60171f0-ccac-4585-95e1-2efc98960f2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":274,"requestId":"2045:328887:7A63B4:8CEF20:69F011DA"},"id":"1d1f0fdf-a29d-438b-84e2-6cb27c771f31","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:48:19.456Z","parentId":"9c7ba263-e507-4773-bb55-a8c4facc358b"}
